BEGIN:VCALENDAR
VERSION:2.0
CALSCALE:GREGORIAN
PRODID:-//Chad Kuehn//Cultural Calendar//EN
X-WR-CALNAME:Cultural Observances
X-WR-TIMEZONE:America/Chicago

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:carnivalbegins-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Carnival Season Begins
DESCRIPTION:Carnival season traditionally begins on Epiphany (January 6\, Three Kings Day) and runs through Mardi Gras. A festive period marked by parades\, masquerades\, and celebrations — especially vibrant in New Orleans\, Rio de Janeiro\, and Venice.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260106
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260107
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:chineseny-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Chinese New Year
DESCRIPTION:The Lunar New Year\, celebrated on the first day of the first month of the Chinese lunisolar calendar. 2026 is the Year of the Fire Horse. A 15-day celebration featuring family reunions\, feasts\, fireworks\, and traditional customs for good luck and prosperity.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260217
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260218
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:groundhogday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Groundhog Day
DESCRIPTION:An American folk tradition on February 2 centered on Punxsutawney Phil\, a groundhog in Pennsylvania. If Phil sees his shadow\, legend says six more weeks of winter\; if not\, an early spring is expected.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260202
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260203
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:valentinesday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Valentine's Day
DESCRIPTION:Celebrated on February 14\, Valentine's Day is a cultural holiday honoring love and affection. Traditions include exchanging cards\, flowers\, chocolates\, and gifts with romantic partners\, friends\, and family.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260214
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260215
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mardigras-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Mardi Gras (Fat Tuesday)
DESCRIPTION:Mardi Gras — French for 'Fat Tuesday' — is the last day of Carnival season\, falling 47 days before Easter. Celebrated with elaborate parades\, masquerade balls\, and feasting before the Lenten season of fasting begins on Ash Wednesday.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260217
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260218
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:stpatricksday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:St. Patrick's Day
DESCRIPTION:Celebrated on March 17\, St. Patrick's Day honors the patron saint of Ireland. Widely observed as a cultural celebration of Irish heritage with parades\, green attire\, and festivities\, particularly in cities with large Irish-American communities.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260317
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260318
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:aprilfools-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:April Fool's Day
DESCRIPTION:April 1 is a lighthearted day of pranks\, jokes\, and hoaxes. Though not an official holiday\, the tradition of fooling friends and family is observed across many cultures worldwide.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260401
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260402
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:earthday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Earth Day
DESCRIPTION:Observed annually on April 22\, Earth Day is an international event dedicated to raising awareness about environmental protection. First celebrated in 1970\, it now mobilizes more than a billion people worldwide around environmental causes.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260422
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260423
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:arborday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Arbor Day
DESCRIPTION:Observed on the last Friday of April\, Arbor Day is a national holiday encouraging the planting and care of trees. Founded in Nebraska in 1872 by J. Sterling Morton\, it is now celebrated in many countries around the world.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260424
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260425
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mayday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:May Day
DESCRIPTION:May 1 is celebrated worldwide as a spring festival and International Workers' Day. In many countries it is an official labor holiday\; in the U.S. it carries folk traditions of maypoles and seasonal renewal.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260501
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260502
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cincodemayo-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Cinco de Mayo
DESCRIPTION:Observed on May 5\, Cinco de Mayo commemorates the Mexican Army's victory over French forces at the Battle of Puebla in 1862. In the United States it has grown into a broad celebration of Mexican culture and heritage.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260505
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260506
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mothersday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Mother's Day
DESCRIPTION:Celebrated on the second Sunday of May\, Mother's Day honors mothers and maternal figures. Established as a national holiday in 1914\, it is marked with flowers\, cards\, gifts\, and family gatherings.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260510
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260511
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:fathersday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Father's Day
DESCRIPTION:Celebrated on the third Sunday of June\, Father's Day honors fathers and paternal figures. First recognized nationally in the early 20th century\, it is marked with gifts\, cards\, and family gatherings.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260621
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260622
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:halloween-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Halloween
DESCRIPTION:Observed on October 31\, Halloween is a cultural holiday rooted in the ancient Celtic festival of Samhain. Modern traditions include costumes\, trick-or-treating\, carving jack-o'-lanterns\, and haunted houses.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261031
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261101
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:blackfriday-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:Black Friday
DESCRIPTION:The day after Thanksgiving\, Black Friday has become one of the busiest retail shopping days of the year in the United States. Named for the tradition of retailers moving from financial losses ('in the red') to profits ('in the black') during the holiday shopping season.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261127
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261128
END:VEVENT

BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:newyearseve-2026@cultural
SUMMARY:New Year's Eve
DESCRIPTION:December 31 marks the last day of the Gregorian calendar year. Celebrated worldwide with countdowns\, fireworks\, parties\, and traditions to welcome the new year at midnight.
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261231
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270101
END:VEVENT

